passages.text: Outlook Becomes Cloudier as CVI Outlook Worsens and Begins to Weigh on FY26

Cooper reported disappointing F3Q25 results after the close on Wednesday with a mixed bag of quarterly results and guidance updates. Starting with the print, sales of \(\) 1.06B\((+2\%\) organic) were in - line to below consensus with a significant organic miss in CVI and an in - line performance in CSI as worsening trends for Clariti globally and a notable weakening in e - commerce trends across APAC. Earnings beat on the bottom by \(\) 0.03\(but largely due to tax\) (+\) 0.02) with in - line gross margin and slightly lower operating spend driving modestly better EBITA (+20bps). With only one quarter left in the fiscal year, management nonetheless had to lower its full - year range on the top - line down to\) \ \(4.076 - 4.096B\) (+4.0- 4.5% organic), a step down from the previous \(\) 4.107- 4.146B\((+5.0 - 6.0\%\) organic) with worse - than - expected trends across both sides of the business. With new challenges from Clariti introduced on today's call and limited visibility into how durable all the company's challenges might be, we think it's prudent to remain on the sidelines until we can see more concrete signs of stabilization.

We think it's prudent to take a more cautious stance on FY26 given the sheer number of puts and takes that look to be impacting growth in the near- term. Cooper didn't provide concrete guidance, but previewed that it expects to grow new fits a step above market with contact lens sales growing at least in- line with the markets \(+4 - 6\%\) following a stabilization in this year's destocking dynamics. CSI should also be positioned to benefit from easy comps in fertility. However, it's hard to buy into this outlook following a year that has fallen short of similarly bullish guidance. With that in mind, we're forecasting CVI growth of \(+4\%\) organic in FY26 to reflect conservatism on both the broader market and competitive dynamics within it, with CSI now forecast to grow \(+4.5\%\) organic off of an easy comp.

Moving on to the P&L, we similarly think it's reasonable to forecast more muted EPS growth closer to mid- single to high- single digits. Management reiterated that its long- term growth target continues to be low double- digit constant currency growth in operating income with tariff headwinds of \(- \mathbb{S}24M\) more than offset by continued operating expense leverage. With a lower growth outlook, tariff headwinds, and worsening price in CVI, however, we're forecasting EPS of \(\) 4.34\((+6\%)\) next year, which reflects modest operating margin expansion of \(+20bps\) to \(25.9\%\) and the aforementioned organic revenue growth.

Turning back to FY25, guidance for both CVI and CSI was lowered again with organic growth of \(+4.0 - 5.0\%\) (vs. \(+6.0 - 7.0\%\) ) and \(+3.0 - 3.5\%\) (vs. \(3.5 - 4.5\%\) ), respectively. This translates into CVI sales of \(\) 700- 713M\((+2.0 - 4.0\%\) organic) in F4Q, well below the Street at closer to\) \ \(729M(+7.0\%\) organic), while CSI sales of \(\) 350- 356M\((+2.0 - 4.0\%\) organic) also comes below consensus at \(\) 360M\((+4.5 - 5.0\%\) organic). The CVI guide reflects continued pressures on Clariti only partially offset by stronger MyDay, although the latter will take time to translate fits and trials into actual revenues. CSI reflects

Cooper's challenges have continued to worsen as ongoing challenges to both CVI and CSI has weighed on the company's ability to deliver consistent quarterly results. While we continue to see a significant opportunity for ongoing mix upgrades and growing penetration in fast- growing areas like myopia management, it's difficult to get bullish on this outlook as fully- year growth takes another step down to reflect moderating market growth, distributor destocking, and weaker Clariti adoption that hasn't fully translated into higher MyDay revenues yet. With execution taking a step back after last year's improvements, we rate shares of COO Neutral as a durable mid- single- digit outlook is balanced against these near- term challenges.

Our December 2026 price target of \(\) 66\(values COO at 14.0x our CY2027 cash EPS estimate. This compares with the large - cap MedTech group currently trading at \(\sim 18.5x\) CY26E EPS, an appropriate discount that reflects concerning near- term challenges to the company's core contact lens business and a string of softer quarters seen so far in FY25.

- Earnings guidance moved up to \(\) 4.08-4.12\(+10 - 11\%\) from the previous \(\) 4.05-4.11\(as the tax - driven beat offsets the lower revenue outlook. Gross margin is expected to be down slightly in F4Q25 from last year's\) 66.9\%\$ to reflect tariffs and a negative mix shift towards MyDay away from Clariti. Operating margin in the quarter is still expected to improve slightly from last year's \(25.9\%\) . Interest expense is forecast at \(\) 21M\(with tax of\) 14 - 15\% \(, with free cash flow of\) \ \(100M\) for the quarter ( \(\) 385M\(for the full year), slightly higher than the midpoint of the previous\) \ \(350 - 400M\) target to reflect the end of a large CVI investment cycle.

- Moving on to the print itself, CVI sales of \(\) 718M\((+2\%\) organic) came in \(\) 3M\(below the Street. Cooper saw another strong quarter from Toric & Multifocals as sales of\) \ \(359M(+6\%\) organic) beat consensus by \(\) 8M\(, offset by a decline in Sphere & Other down to\) \ \(360M(- 1\%\) organic) that missed by \(\) 10M\(. Elevated fitting activity from MyDay drove double - digit growth but looks to have detracted from Clariti sales in markets where the differentiation between the two devices has not been in focus. Daily shiy still grew +7\% with multifocals up +20\%\), with the broader market still tracking to mid - single digits.

- Looking specifically at Myopia Management, MiSight grew +23\% with a record quarter in EMEA as new pricing promotions begin to gain traction. Performance in the Americas was more mixed as a result of a new promotional structure that hasn't begun bearing fruit yet, while Japan is set to begin commercialization in early 2026 and the new MyDay MiSight is set to begin launching in Europe and parts of APAC in the first half of next year.

- CSI sales of \(\) 342M(+2\%\$ organic) came in - line with the Street. Office and Surgical sales of \(\) 205M(+1\%\(organic) came in slightly below the Street despite double - digit growth in labor & delivery and high single - digit growth in specialty surgical. Paragard declined -10\% to reflect advanced purchasing earlier in the year but is forecast to see some growth in F4Q ahead of another year of similar challenges in FY26. Fertility sales of\) \ \(137M(+3\%\) organic) came in slightly better as strength in genomics and consumables was able to offset pressure on capital purchases and ongoing softness in APAC.

- Down the P&L, gross margin of \(67.3\%\) was in - line to above consensus with benefits from mix and positive Fx, while SG&A of \(37.0\%\) was lower (-30bps) and R&D of \(4.2\%\) was higher (+20bps). This drove operating margin of \(26.1\%\), -20bps ahead of the Street. All told, when coupled with a better tax rate (-70bps), this drove cash EPS of \(\) 0.96\(ahead of the Street at\) \ \(0.93\)

- We are establishing a December 2026 price target of \(\) 66\(, or\) 14.0x CY27E earnings. This values Cooper at a discount to its large - cap MedTech peer group trading at -18.5x CY26E earnings, an appropriate discount that reflects concerning near - term challenges to the company's core contact lens business and a string of softer quarters seen so far in FY25.
